qas.question: What is quark matter usually thought of as?
What is nuclear matter similar to?
At low density, what is expected of strange matter?
What kind of core does nuclear matter occur in?
What has Strange matter been definitely proven to occur as?

context: <b1_0>Strange matter<b1_0/> is a particular form of quark matter, usually thought of as a <b0_0>liquid<b0_0/> of up, down, and strange quarks. It is contrasted with nuclear matter, which is a liquid of neutrons and protons (which themselves are built out of up and down quarks), and with non-strange quark matter, which is a quark liquid that contains only up and down quarks. At high enough density, strange matter is expected <b2_0>to be color superconducting<b2_0/>. Strange matter is hypothesized to occur in the core of <b3_0>neutron stars<b3_0/>, or, more speculatively, as <b4_0>isolated droplets<b4_0/> that may vary in size from femtometers (strangelets) to kilometers (quark stars).
